# 2026-06-29-12-00 CST -- XRP -- LOSS -$100  (win 38%, n=8, fire 67%)

CST 12:00 hour == UTC 04:00-04:59. PAPER signal at $1000/market notional. Real money was
~$1 probes (mode=LIVE fills tiny, ~2 shares); the -$100 is the paper signal. XRP was still
live this hour (stopped ~14:32 CST, ~2.5h later). Sum of the 8 nonzero round pnls = -$99.76.

## What happened
8 trades fired this hour (rounds 32-43; 12 rounds, 4 no-trade). 5 losses, 3 wins = 37.5% ~ 38%.
The loss was BROAD, not 1-2 blowups -- five near-full -$24..-$26 losses dominate:

  rnd  side  winner  pnl       entry  result   round window (UTC)
  r32  NO    YES     -25.68    0.76   LOSS     04:00-04:05
  r34  NO    NO       +4.29    0.00*  WIN      04:05-04:10  (*real fill 0 shares; paper won)
  r36  YES   NO      -25.15    0.78   LOSS     04:15-04:20
  r37  NO    YES     -16.76    0.75   LOSS     04:20-04:25  (smaller size -> -16 not -25)
  r38  YES   YES      +6.57    0.78   WIN      04:25-04:30
  r39  NO    NO       +5.15    0.83   WIN      04:30-04:35
  r40  YES   NO      -24.39    0.76   LOSS     04:35-04:40
  r42  NO    YES     -23.78    0.77   LOSS     04:45-04:50

Losses split BOTH directions: 3 down-favorites (NO) lost, 2 up-favorites (YES) lost.
Favorites got upset both ways -- the signature of a whippy tape pinning the strike, NOT a
one-sided directional sweep that would flip only one side. Win 38% on 8 = exactly 3/8.
"fire 67%" = trades fired / rounds (8/12).

## Entry prices
All entries in-band (0.75-0.83), i.e. NOT systematically bought-high; mix of band:
  r32 NO 0.76 | r36 YES 0.78 | r37 NO 0.75 | r39 NO 0.83 | r40 YES 0.76 | r42 NO 0.77
Execution (ledger, mode=LIVE real fills vs paper_price):
  - Fills were AT or slightly BETTER than paper most rounds (e.g. r32 fill 0.7600 vs paper
    0.7767; r42 fill 0.7700 vs paper 0.7911) -> no adverse slippage; if anything the real
    fills got a better price than the paper mark. Paper pnl is the conservative case here.
  - r34: real FILL = 0.0 price / 0.0 shares -> zero real fill (book too thin to fill the $1
    probe), yet paper settled it as a +4.29 win. Counted as a paper win it did not really earn.
  - r37: filled but smaller -> loss only -16.76 vs the ~-25 full losses.
Depth at entry (market_data ticks, L1 ask size in the 0.76-0.85 band):
  - XRP L1 book median ~8-22 shares per level (r36 med 8.7, r38 med 22, r42 single sample 10).
  - Confirms the known thin XRP book (~21 vs BTC ~381). r40 had only n_ticks=8 for the whole
    round (near-dead book). So: thin, yes -- but the bot did NOT buy high; entries were fine.
Verdict on execution: NOT the cause. No adverse fills; real fills beat paper. The -$100 is a
clean favorites-lost-at-settlement loss, not a slippage/microstructure loss.

## Spot context
Binance XRPUSDT 1-min, UTC 04:00-04:59:
  Hour open 1.0509 -> close 1.0422, net -0.828%. High 1.0509 / low 1.0421, total range 0.84%.
  Steady grind DOWN with constant reversals: 28 of 59 minute-to-minute direction flips;
  sum|1m moves| 0.0298 vs net|move| 0.0087 -> chop ratio 3.43x (price travelled ~3.4x its net
  displacement). Tight band, low amplitude, high reversal count = textbook XRP chop, but with a
  mild persistent down-drift.
Per-5min round close-to-close were tiny (mostly +/-0.05% to -0.22%), so most rounds settled on
a near-coin-flip distance from strike -- exactly the regime where a 76-85c "favorite" carries
almost no real edge and individual outcomes are near 50/50. The down-drift alone doesn't
explain the losses (NO/down-favorites lost too), confirming chop-near-strike over direction.

## vs normal
XRP typical win ~78-83%. Observed 3/8 = 38%.
Binomial (one-sided, P of <= 3 wins in 8):
  p=0.78 -> 0.0158 (E[wins] 6.2) ; p=0.80 -> 0.0104 (E[wins] 6.4) ; p=0.83 -> 0.0050.
So a result THIS bad or worse has ~1-1.6% probability per hour at the assumed true win rate.
Unusual (roughly a 1-in-65 to 1-in-200 hour), but the sample is only 8 trades and the bot runs
many coin-hours per day, so seeing one such tail hour somewhere is expected, not alarming. The
dollar size (-$100) looks dramatic only because each loss is ~-$25 at $1000 notional on a ~0.78
entry (lose ~0.78, the geometry amplifies a 5-loss cluster).

## Verdict: VARIANCE or SIGNAL
VARIANCE, with a SIGNAL-flavored backdrop -- but variance dominates THIS hour.
  - For SIGNAL you'd want: a one-sided directional spot event flipping only one side of
    favorites, OR bought-high/adverse-fill execution. Neither holds: losses hit BOTH
    directions, entries were in-band, real fills beat paper, no slippage.
  - The 38% is a ~1-1.5% tail draw on 8 trades. That is improbable for a single hour but fully
    consistent with normal variance once you account for many coin-hours sampled per day.
  - The one structural truth visible here: XRP's edge is THIN and FRAGILE. The book was thin
    (L1 ~8-22, one round near-dead at 8 ticks; r34 couldn't even get a real fill), and the tape
    was choppy near the strike (chop ratio 3.4x, 28 flips), so 5-min favorites behaved like
    coin-flips. That fragility is WHY a bad 8-trade hour shows up as a clean -$100 cluster -- and
    it is the same fragility the RCA flagged and that got XRP stopped ~2.5h later.
Bottom line: this specific -$100 hour = bad-variance cluster (5 favorites lost across both
directions in choppy-near-strike conditions), not a discrete signal/execution event. Do not
over-claim from one hour; it is corroborating evidence for "XRP edge too thin," not a new cause.

## Action
- No code/exec fix indicated for this hour: fills were clean, entries in-band. Nothing to patch
  at the microstructure level from this event.
- Treat as confirming the existing thin-edge thesis. The later XRP stop (~14:32 CST) is the
  correct response; this hour is one data point supporting it, not the trigger by itself.
- If re-enabling XRP is ever considered: require a thicker-book gate (skip rounds where L1 size
  in-band < threshold, e.g. < ~15-20 shares -- r34/r40 would have been skipped) and/or a chop
  filter (skip when recent 1-min flip-rate / chop-ratio is high), since near-strike chop is
  where the 76-85c favorite has no edge. Keep XRP notional below the other coins until win rate
  is re-validated over a larger n.
- Monitoring: flag any coin-hour with <= 3/8 wins for review, but do not act on a single
  8-trade tail; require a multi-hour trend before concluding signal/regime change.
